@* Demonstrates two trigger styles: imperative response header and attribute-driven header. *@
<section class="panel">
    <h2>Server Trigger</h2>
    <p>Demonstrates fragment swaps plus `HX-Trigger` events from response headers.</p>
</section>

<section id="server-trigger-demo" class="panel">
    <h3>Server Trigger</h3>
    <p class="empty">Compare trigger payload from action code vs `[HtmxResponse]` attribute.</p>
    <div class="demo-note" role="note">
        <strong>How To Test:</strong> Click either button and compare the toast body with the inspector's
        <code>HX-Trigger</code> response header.
    </div>
    <p class="demo-caption">
        Expected outcome: both buttons render a toast, but the source of the trigger header differs.
    </p>

    @* Action method emits trigger payload directly in controller body. *@
    <button
        type="button"
        hx-get="/fragments/toast/success"
        hx-target="#toast-region"
        hx-swap="innerHTML">
        Trigger Toast (Body Trigger)
    </button>

    @* Action uses [HtmxResponse] attribute to emit trigger header after execution. *@
    <button
        type="button"
        hx-get="/fragments/toast/success-attribute"
        hx-target="#toast-region"
        hx-swap="innerHTML">
        Trigger Toast (Attribute Trigger)
    </button>
    <div id="toast-region"></div>
    <p id="event-log" aria-live="polite">No server events yet.</p>
</section>

<script>
    // Client-side listener for server-triggered custom events.
    document.body.addEventListener("toast:show", function (event) {
        var detail = event.detail || {};
        var message = detail.message || "Server event received.";
        var log = document.getElementById("event-log");
        if (log) {
            log.textContent = message;
        }
    });
</script>
